@chapter Clients
@cindex Clients

@dfn{Clients} are programs that work in cooperation with
@dfn{KRSNAke} to provide the user with extended functionality or
additional information.  @dfn{KRSNAke} is the @dfn{server} in this
connection, and the clients basically receive various types of
information from @dfn{KRSNAke}, which they may choose either to
ignore or to act upon in a given way, usually defining the function
of the given client.

When KRSNAke starts, it looks for a subdirectory called
@file{Clients} in its home directory.  All files found in this
directory will be launched.  If they are KRSNAke clients, they should
attach themselves to KRSNAke and function as they're expected to.  If
they're other programs, they'll be started too - but generally you
shouldn't put anything besides KRSNAke clients in the "Clients"
directory.

At present, there are two KRSNAke clients available; the @file{Hall of Fame}
and the @file{Action Replay}.  The former records high scores, the
latter records games for subsequent replay.  See their individual
descriptions for more details.

@menu
Available clients

* Hall of Fame::                  High scores
* Action Replay::                 Game recorder
@end menu


@node Hall of Fame, Action Replay, Clients, Clients
@section The Hall of Fame
@cindex Hall of Fame
@cindex Clients, Hall of Fame
@cindex MultiUserFileSystem
@cindex Crassus, Marcus Licinius
@cindex Masonry
@cindex Knights Templar
@cindex Templars
@cindex Rosicrucians

This client keeps track of high scores.  Each player has only one
entry @minus{} this is contrary to most high score tables, but as the
Hall of Fame can handle an unlimited number of entries, this helps
cut back a little on the table size.

The default name offered the player the first time the Hall of Fame
registers a high score is taken from the system variable @var{USER}.
@dfn{MultiUserFileSystem} and similar applications usually maintain
this variable.  If it is not present, the @dfn{Hall of Fame} reverts
to @samp{Crassus}.  The default name is stored in the snapshot file
whenever the @dfn{Hall of Fame} exits, and the name stored here is
used if it exists.

If you're intimidated by the default entries, being such
conspiratorial characters as Templars, Masons and Rosicrucians, you
can replace the file @file{ENVARC:KRSNAke/HallOfFame.data} with an
empty file, and you'll have a blank Hall of Fame.  But really, that's
being rather paranoid.


